03905nam a22006255i 9780674269262DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222004mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742692627 a10.4159/97806742692622doi  a(DE-B1597)589752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aML410.B8bB42 2004eb 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a780/.922231 aBeller-McKenna, Daniel., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBrahms and the German Spirit /cDaniel. Beller-McKenna. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Introduction: Brahms and the German Spirit -- t2 Religion, Language, and Luther’s Bible -- t3 Ein deutsches Requiem, Op. 45, and the Apocalyptic Paradigm -- t4 The Triumphlied, Op. 55, and the Apocalyptic Moment -- t5 Gebet einer König: National Prayers in the Fest- und Gedenksprüche, Op. 109 -- t6 Beyond the End -- tAPPENDIX Longer Musical Examples -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe music of Johannes Brahms is deeply colored, Daniel Beller-McKenna shows, by nineteenth-century German nationalism and by Lutheran religion. Focusing on the composer's choral works, the author offers new insight on the cultural grounding for Brahms's music. Music historians have been reluctant to address Brahms's Germanness, wary perhaps of fascist implications. Beller-McKenna counters this tendency; by giving an account of the intertwining of nationalism, politics, and religion that underlies major works, he restores Brahms to his place in nineteenth-century German culture. The author explores Brahms's interest in the folk element in old church music; the intense national pride expressed in works such as the Triumphlied; the ways Luther's Bible and Lutheranism are reflected in Brahms's music; and the composer's ideas about nation building. The final chapter looks at Brahms's nationalistic image as employed by the National Socialists, 1933-1945, and as witnessed earlier in the century (including the complication of rumors that Brahms was Jewish). In comparison to the overtly nationalist element in Wagner's music, the German elements in Brahms's style have been easy to overlook. This nuanced study uncovers those nationalistic elements, enriching our understanding both of Brahms's art and of German culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aMusiczGermanyy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNationalism in music. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674269262zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269262423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269262/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK